      <hedline>
        <hl1>Palestinian Textbooks</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>June Elliot letter on Sept 13 report about Palestinian children using textbooks that give distorted picture of Israel and Jerusalem's history</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>According to '' 'A' Is for Arafat, 'B' Is for Bethlehem' '' (news article, Sept. 13), Palestinian children now study textbooks in which maps do not include Israel, Arab terrorism is never mentioned and Israel (along with Britain) is labeled one of only two 20th-century occupiers of Palestine.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>According to '' 'A' Is for Arafat, 'B' Is for Bethlehem' '' (news article, Sept. 13), Palestinian children now study textbooks in which maps do not include Israel, Arab terrorism is never mentioned and Israel (along with Britain) is labeled one of only two 20th-century occupiers of Palestine.</p>
        <p>By pretending that Tel Aviv doesn't exist and by ignoring Turkish and Jordanian involvement in Jerusalem, Yasir Arafat and the Palestinians reveal themselves as revisionist historians as well as insincere partners for peace.</p>
        <p>Such texts will only produce yet another generation of Palestinians who resent Israel and who are ignorant of facts: that Palestinians were offered -- and refused -- a state in 1947, and that instead of accepting responsibility for their refusal or acknowledging their abandonment by their Arab brothers, they now demand rewards, one of which is Jerusalem.</p>
        <p>JUNE ELLIOT  Oakland, Calif., Sept. 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
